results.name: a(n) = gcd(n, A032741(n)) where A032741(n) is the number of proper divisors of n.
comment: Do all values appear? - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Jan 23 2007
a(n) = 1 if n = p^k, p prime, k >= 0 and k <> p or,
a(n) = 2 if n = 2^2 or n = 2^(2*p), p prime <> 2,
a(n) = 3 if n = 3*p, p prime <> 3 or n = 3^3,
a(n) = 5 if n = 5*p^2, p prime <> 5, or n = 25*p, p prime <> 5, or n = 5^5,
a(n) = 7 if n = 7*p*q with p<q primes <> 7 or n = 7*p^3, p prime <> 7, or n = 7^7,
a(n) = p if n = p^p, p prime. (End)
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..65537
example: a(6)=3 because 6 has 3 proper divisors {1,2,3} and gcd(6,3) is 3.
